Support Vector Machines in R

For DATA50XX by ctong

Overview

Support Vector Machines (SVMs) are supervised learning models used for both classification and regression tasks. At their core, SVMs aim to find the optimal hyperplane to serve as a decision boundary to best separate observations into different classes.

Margin and Support Vectors

Margin is defined as the distance between the decision boundary (the separating hyperplane) and the closest data points from each class. These closest points are called support vectors. They directly influence the position and orientation of the hyperplane.

Example: A 2D separating hyperplane is line

Hard versus Soft Margins

Hard Margin: Applies when data is perfectly linearly separable. SVM finds the hyperplane that maximizes the margin without any misclassifications. A wider margin produces a more robust with improved generalization to unseen data.

Soft Margin: Allows for some misclassifications to accommodate noisy and overlapping data. A penalty parameter controls the trade-off between maximizing margin and minimizing misclassifications.

Kernel Functions

Kernel Functions transform data into a higher-dimensional space to make observations of different class more easily separable by a hyperplane.

Example: 1D to 2D

Example: 2D to 3D

Kernel Trick

Computation of similarity measures in high-dimensional space for determining decision boundary without explicitly transforming the data, saving computational resources.

Similarity

Similarity is measured using mathematical functions related to distance between the data points. A high similarity value means the points are close together, while a low similarity means they are far apart.

When a kernel function is applied, SVM builds its model using pairwise similarities rather than raw feature values. This emulates the transformation of non-linearly separable data into a higher dimensional space for computing a separating hyperplane (decision boundary) without actually transforming the data.

For example, the Radial Basis Function (RBF) kernel computes similarity as:

\[ K(x, x') = \exp(-\gamma \|x - x'\|^2) \]

  • If x and x' are very similar (i.e., close), the computed value is close to 1.
  • If they are very different (far apart), the computed value is close to 0.

The positioning of the decision boundary is influenced only by the most critical points (support vectors) through their similarity to other data points. If a support vector is similar to many nearby points, the model will rely more heavily on that SV to determine where the boundary should go. In other words, similarity values help determine the shape and position of the decision boundary.

Classification versus Regression

  • SVM Classification: Finds a boundary that best separates classes.
  • SVM Regression (SVR): Tries to fit the best possible line (or curve) that stays within an acceptable error margin from the actual data points.

Linear Kernel

A linear kernel assumes the data can be separated using a straight line (or hyperplane). It is best suited for linearly separable data.

library(caret)
library(kernlab)
library(e1071)

data(iris)

## Only use 2 classes for binary classification
iris_binary <- subset(iris, Species != "setosa")
iris_binary$Species <- factor(iris_binary$Species)

## Set up cross-validation
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5)

## Train linear SVM
set.seed(123)
svm_linear <- train(Species ~ Petal.Length + Petal.Width, data = iris_binary, 
                    method = "svmLinear",
                    trControl = ctrl,
                   tuneLength=5)

svm_linear

svm_linear$finalModel
## Support Vector Machine object of class "ksvm" 
## 
## SV type: C-svc  (classification) 
##  parameter : cost C = 1 
## 
## Linear (vanilla) kernel function. 
## 
## Number of Support Vectors : 19

## Objective Function Value : -14.6831 
## Training error : 0.06
pl_range <- seq(min(iris_binary$Petal.Length) - 0.5, max(iris_binary$Petal.Length) + 0.5, length = 200)
pw_range <- seq(min(iris_binary$Petal.Width)  - 0.5, max(iris_binary$Petal.Width)  + 0.5, length = 200)
grid <- expand.grid(Petal.Length = pl_range, Petal.Width = pw_range)

# 5. Predict class on the grid
grid$Predicted <- predict(svm_linear, newdata = grid)

# 6. Plot data and decision regions
ggplot() +
  # background colored by predicted class
  geom_tile(data = grid, aes(x = Petal.Length, y = Petal.Width, fill = Predicted), alpha = 0.3) +
  # original points on top
  geom_point(data = iris_binary, aes(x = Petal.Length, y = Petal.Width, shape = Species, color = Species), size = 2) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("versicolor" = "#A6CEE3", "virginica" = "#B2DF8A")) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("versicolor" = "#1F78B4", "virginica" = "#33A02C")) +
  labs(
    title = "Linear SVM Decision Boundary\nversicolor vs virginica",
    x = "Petal Length",
    y = "Petal Width",
    fill = "Region",
    color = "Actual Species"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Hyperparameters

  • C (Cost): Controls the trade-off between margin size and classification error. Lower values allow a larger margin but more errors.

Interpreting Output

  • Accuracy: Proportion of correctly classified samples in cross-validation.
  • Best Tune: Shows which value of C yielded the best performance.

Polynomial Kernel

Polynomial kernels allow modeling more complex boundaries by considering interactions of features up to a specified degree.

set.seed(123)
svm_poly <- train(Species ~ ., data = iris_binary, 
                  method = "svmPoly",
                  trControl = ctrl,
                  tuneLength = 5)

Hyperparameters

  • Degree: The polynomial degree.
  • Scale: Scaling parameter.
  • C (Cost): Controls the trade-off between margin size and classification error. Lower values allow a larger margin but more errors.

Interpreting Output

Look for the best combination of degree, scale, and cost that yields highest cross-validated accuracy.

RBF Kernel

The Radial Basic Function (RBF) handles non-linear boundaries by using a bell-shaped function to measure similarity.

set.seed(123)
svm_rbf <- train(Species ~ ., data = iris_binary, 
                 method = "svmRadial",
                 trControl = ctrl,
                 tuneLength = 5)

svm_rbf

Hyperparameters

  • Sigma: Defines the radius of influence of a support vector.
  • C (Cost): Controls the trade-off between margin size and classification error. Lower values allow a larger margin but more errors.

Interpreting Output

Best performance is achieved by balancing the flexibility of the model (sigma) and regularization (C).

Support Vector Regression

SVR fits a function within a margin of tolerance (epsilon). Only data points outside this margin influence the model.

data(cars)

ctrl_reg <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5)

set.seed(123)
svr_rbf <- train(Mileage ~ Cylinder, data = cars,
                 method = "svmRadial",
                 trControl = ctrl_reg,
                 tuneLength = 5)

svr_rbf

Hyperparameters

  • C: Penalty for errors outside the epsilon-tube.
  • Epsilon: Width of the margin of tolerance.
  • Sigma: For radial kernel.

Kernel Specification

In caret: - method = "svmLinear" for linear - method = "svmPoly" for polynomial - method = "svmRadial" for RBF

Summary

Comparison of SVM Kernels

This document compares Support Vector Machine (SVM) kernelsLinear, Polynomial, and Radial Basis Function (RBF)in terms of their strengths, limitations, and when each is most appropriate.

Linear Kernel

Pros

  • Fast to compute, especially on large datasets.
  • Easier to interpret due to linear decision boundary.
  • Fewer hyperparametersonly regularization parameter C.
  • Works well with high-dimensional, sparse datasets (e.g., text classification).

Cons

  • Limited flexibilitycant model complex non-linear boundaries.
  • Risk of underfitting if the data is not linearly separable.

When to Use

  • When the data is approximately linearly separable.
  • When interpretability and speed are important.
  • When working with high-dimensional or sparse data.

Polynomial Kernel

Pros

  • Captures interactions between features through polynomial terms.
  • Tunable complexity via degree parameter.
  • Useful when feature interactions are known to be polynomial.

Cons

  • More computationally expensive than linear.
  • More hyperparameters (degree, scale, C) require careful tuning.
  • Can overfit, especially at high degrees.

When to Use

  • When the relationship between features is polynomial.
  • When you need a more flexible model than linear but want to avoid the full complexity of RBF.

RBF Kernel

Pros

  • Highly flexible and powerful for non-linear decision boundaries.
  • Good accuracy across a wide variety of datasets.
  • Automatically adapts to data complexity via sigma or gamma.

Cons

  • Can overfit if not properly tuned.
  • Less interpretable due to complex feature space transformations.
  • Slower to train, especially on large datasets.

When to Use

  • When data has complex, non-linear patterns.
  • When prediction accuracy is prioritized over interpretability.
  • When adequate computational resources are available.

Summary Comparison Table

Kernel Type Pros Cons Best When
Linear Fast, interpretable, good with sparse data Cannot model non-linearity Data is linearly separable or high-dimensional
Polynomial Captures feature interactions, moderate complexity Slower, risk of overfitting with high degrees Data has polynomial feature interactions
RBF Highly flexible, best accuracy in many cases Less interpretable, slower, tuning sensitive Complex non-linear data, accuracy matters
